gomodel:SYNGO_3783  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.2: \"Parkin interacts with GluK2\"\nFig.3: \"Parkin ubiquitinates GluK2\"\nFig.4: \"Loss of parkin function increases surface GluK2 levels, KAR currents and causes excitotoxicity\"\n\nNote:\n- Parkin, PARK2 is a ubiquitin ligase that modifies the KAR thereby regulating its surface expression.\n- Data on synaptic KARs is not included in this paper but implied by the authors. However, the authors mention: \"Parkin also mediates endophilin-A1 ubiquitination and some evidence suggests that endophilin-A-mediated parkin recruitment promotes synaptic protein ubiquitination9. The loss of endogenous parkin sensitizes in vitro midbrain dopaminergic neurons to kainate toxicity10, increases excitatory glutamatergic synapse numbers and increases vulnerability to synaptic excitotoxicity in cultured hippocampal neurons6. Hence, although current knowledge strongly suggests that parkin intervenes in modulating glutamatergic synapse function, the underlying molecular mechanism is unknown. We hypothesized that parkin may directly regulate ionotropic glutamate receptors of the N-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDAR), α-amino-3-hydroxy-5-methyl-4-isoxazolepropionic acid (AMPAR) or kainate receptor (KAR) types. Our results show that parkin regulates KAR function and suggest that KAR may have a pathogenetic role in parkin-related ARJP.\". Experimental description: - \"Plasmids encoding complementary DNA for human parkin and parkin domains (Ubl-linker, aa 1-237; RING1, aa 217-310; RING2, aa 395-465) were described previously36.\"\n- \"Primary rat hippocampal neurons were prepared from embryonic day 18-19 rat brains\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-29" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3783" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

